    <stitle>Bosch Parking Brake: Manual or Power Brake - PARK BRAKE: POWER BRAKE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="10">
        <title>PARK BRAKE: POWER BRAKE</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Please review the following general information.</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>The air actuated parking brake is equipped with an air gauge and warning light. When the air
                        pressure in the parking brake air storage system has been reduced to approximately 70 psi (483
                        kPA), the light will activate.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>If air pressure is reduced to approximately 30 psi (207 kPA), the parking brake control knob
                        will automatically pop out and apply the parking brake.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Upon loss of air pressure, partial parking brake application will occur prior to automatic
                        application of the control valve.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>If the parking brake will not release and the vehicle must be moved, the spring chamber must
                        be manually caged by turning the cable adjustment rod counter-clockwise until the spring is
                        caged in the chamber.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, serious personal injury or possibly death, when manually releasing
                        the spring chamber assembly, be sure to block the wheels so that the vehicle cannot move when
                        the parking brake is released.
                    </para>
                </warning>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, serious personal injury or possibly death, never attempt to
                        disassemble the power park brake spring chamber assembly. This part is not serviceable.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Manually Releasing Power Parking Brake</title>
            <para>To manually release the power parking brake follow Step One (1), and Step Four (4) of the instruction
                section SPRING CHAMBER ASSEMBLY: REMOVE. When the cable adjustment rod is sufficiently un-threaded,
                tension on the brake cable will be relaxed and the brake will release.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Rod Stroke Sensor: Remove</title>
            <figure id="f0404407" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404407.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Rod Stroke Sensor Overview</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. ROD STROKE SENSOR</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SENSOR HARNESS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0404408" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404408.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Disconnect Harness</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect rod stroke sensor harness
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404408">(Figure 5)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0404409" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404409.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Rod Stroke Sensor Retaining Screws</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. TWO RETAINING SCREWS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the two retaining screws
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404409">(Figure 6)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0404410" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404410.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Rod Stroke Sensor</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove rod stroke sensor
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404410">(Figure 7)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Sensor aperture must be protected from debris. If no appropriate size caps are available, the
                        aperture can be covered with electrical tape, or suitable alternative.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Rod Stroke Sensor: Install</title>
            <figure id="f0404411" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figG04/G0404407.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Rod Stroke Sensor and Harness</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. ROD STROKE SENSOR</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SENSOR HARNESS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect harness
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404411">(Figure 8)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install sensor
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404410">(Figure 7</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404411">Figure 8)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install retaining screws
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404409">(Figure 6</hotlnk>and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404411">Figure 8)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Spring Chamber Assembly: Remove</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dump air from the system with the dash panel park brake knob. Do not bleed the air
                    tank.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0404412" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404412.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                         scalefitheight="432px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Air Brake Overview</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. AIR TANK</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. AIR LINE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SPRING CHAMBER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect air line from the spring chamber
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404412">(Item 3, Figure 9)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect rod stroke sensor wire harnesses
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404411">(Figure 8)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0404414" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404414.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="256px"
                         scalefitheight="432px"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. Spring Chamber Assembly</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. JAM NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. CABLE ADJUSTMENT ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. CABLE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen jam nut and un-thread adjustment rod from chamber to reduce tension on the cable.
                    Continue to un-thread adjustment rod all the way and remove from chamber
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404414">(Figure 10).</hotlnk>
                    <emph type="bold">Nut and shaft are metric.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0404415" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404415.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. Spring Brake Chamber</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove (2) brake chamber mounting nuts from frame rail.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove brake chamber.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Spring Chamber Assembly: Install</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the rod stroke sensor has been removed, install it before installing the spring
                    chamber.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start threads of cable adjustment rod before installing the chamber on the frame rail.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mount chamber on frame rail. Tighten mounting nuts 55 to 60 lbf-ft. (75 to 81 Nm) of
                    torque.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Connect stroke sensor harness.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reconnect the airline to front of the spring chamber and charge the spring chamber by
                    moving the dash panel park brake knob to the 'out' or released position. This will extend the cable
                    adjustment rod and ease threading the cable.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0404416" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404416.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 12. Threaded Adjustment Rod With Groove</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. GROOVE ON CABLE ADJUSTMENT ROD</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. JAM NUT</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0404417" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg04/g0404417.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. Adjustment Rod With Groove</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. GROOVE ALIGNED WITH SHAFT</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Thread the cable adjustment rod into the cylinder until the groove lines up with the
                    cylinder
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404416">(Figure 12</hotlnk>
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0404417">and Figure 13)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten the jam nut.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
